om":"Dorset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England"},"en":{"Abt 1318–Deceased":"about 1318–Deceased","1315–1348":"1315–1348","1318–Female":"1318–Deceased","1315–1347":"1315–1347","1336–1401":"1336–1401","1274–1336":"1274–1336","1292–1344":"1292–1344","1348":"1348","1315":"1315","1336":"1336","1347":"1347","1401":"1401","1344":"1344","1274":"1274","27 August 1312":"27 August 1312","Abt 1318":"about 1318","1292":"1292","1318":"1318","Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Dorset, England, United Kingdom","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beauchamp","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Antoine, Jacques, Yves, Andre, Armand, Emile, Fernand, Marcel, Marthe, Remi, Alcide, Camille.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of several places in France, for example in Manche and Somme, that are named with Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>champ(s)</i> ‘field, plain’ (from Latin <i>bello campo</i> ‘beautiful field’). In English the surname is generally pronounced   Beecham  . Compare   Bushaw  .","English: in some cases, an Anglo-Norman French adaptation of Scottish   Campbell  , by translation into French of the folk etymology <i>de campo bello</i> ‘from the fair field’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beecham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Beauchamp  , reflecting the normal English pronunciation."]},{"name":"Beachem","meanings":["English (Somerset and Gloucestershire): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Beachum","meanings":["Altered form of English   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Bagent","meanings":["English:","possibly a colloquial pronunciation of   Beauchamp   or   Beecham  . Old French <i>Beau-</i> often appears as <i>Be(e)-</i> in English surnames. The <i>-ch-</i> has been voiced and excrescent <i>-t</i> has been added.","perhaps an Anglicized form of a French or Flemish surname such as <b>Beaujean</b> and <b>Bejean</b>, from Old French <i>bel Jehan</i> ‘handsome John’ + excrescent <i>-t</i>. It could have been introduced to England in the 15th or 16th century by Flemish migrants."]},{"name":"Beacham","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Campbell","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from Gaelic <i>cam</i> ‘crooked, bent’ + <i>beul</i> ‘mouth’. As a result of folk etymology, the surname was often represented in Latin documents as <i>de bello campo</i> ‘of the fair field’, which led to the name sometimes being ‘translated’ into Anglo-Norman French as   Beauchamp  .","Irish (North Armagh): adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Cathmhaoil</b> ‘son of Cathmhaol’ (literally ‘battle chief’): see   Caulfield   and   Cowell  .","English: variant of   Camel  , under the influence of the Scottish name (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Bushaw","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Beauchamp   and   Bouchard  ."]},{"name":"Beacom","meanings":["English (Somerset) and Irish (Fermanagh): of Norman origin, a variant of   Beauchamp  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan Beauchamp was born about 1318, in Dorset, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir John Beauchamp, was 45 and her mother, Joan Nonant, was 28. She married John Chudleigh lll of Broadclist about 1340, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt 1318–Deceased":"umbes 1318–Surnud","1315–1348":"1315–1348","1318–Female":"1318–Surnud","1315–1347":"1315–1347","1336–1401":"1336–1401","1274–1336":"1274–1336","1292–1344":"1292–1344","1348":"1348","1315":"1315","1336":"1336","1347":"1347","1401":"1401","1344":"1344","1274":"1274","27 August 1312":"27. august 1312","Abt 1318":"umbes 1318","1292":"1292","1318":"1318","Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1318–Deceased":"noin 1318–Kuollut","1315–1348":"1315–1348","1318–Female":"1318–Kuollut","1315–1347":"1315–1347","1336–1401":"1336–1401","1274–1336":"1274–1336","1292–1344":"1292–1344","1348":"1348","1315":"1315","1336":"1336","1347":"1347","1401":"1401","1344":"1344","1274":"1274","27 August 1312":"27. elokuuta 1312","Abt 1318":"noin 1318","1292":"1292","1318":"1318","Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Dorset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England"},"fr":{"Abt 131